<DOC><DOCNO> AP880227-0061 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-02-27-88 0833EST</FILEID><FIRST>r i PM-Italy-NewsStrike     02-27 0223</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Italy-News Strike,0230</SECOND><HEAD>Journalists Go On Nationwide Strike</HEAD><DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Italian journalists today began a nationwide strikeintended to prevent publication of daily newspapers on Sunday andMonday.   The walkout, called to protest a breakdown in negotiations for anew contract, will extend to radio and television journalistsSunday and Monday.   Transmitters of the nation's main news agencies, ANSA and AGI,went silent at 7 a.m.   The strike will rob readers of news of Italy's Olympic skiinghero Alberto Tomba, who was going for a second gold medal. However,the race was being broadcast live on three channels.   The strike is the latest in a series of job actions byjournalists. The journalists, whose contracts expired in Decmeber,are seeking pay increases and control over new technology.   In a related development, the price for daily newspapers isbeing raised 8 cents to 72 cents beginning next Tuesday.   Italians also faced other strikes this weekend.   Airport ground personnel scheduled a 24-hour walkout Sunday in acontinuing contract dispute, causing the state-run AlitaliaAirlines to cancel many flights to and from Rome's Leonardo daVinci airport. The airline said intercontinental flights wouldoperate on schedule.   Many schools across Italy, which are normally open Saturdaymorning, were shut down as a result of a strike by teachersdemanding higher pay and better working conditions.</TEXT></DOC>